text:
Today, we celebrate the
journey of the 2024 graduates and the path that
they have taken,

the excitement of discovery,
despair when obstacles seem

endless, pushing
through self-doubt and the doubts of others, and
those moments when an idea just

takes your breath away. Inspiration and perseverance
are at the heart of their story,

but so is passion, curiosity,
and asking the right questions.

With this in mind, let's
take a moment to ask-- to explore an age-old question.

Do the clothes make the person? Academic regalia was first
worn by medieval scholars,

possibly to stay warm
in unheated monasteries. The long gowns, hoods, and caps
were adopted by English scholars

towards the end of
the 14th century, and in the late 19th century,
Harvard faculty began to wear

academic regalia. Today, decoration and symbolism
have superseded function.

The wearing of academic
regalia is mainly reserved for commencement
and other special occasions

at universities and
colleges around the globe. Seriously, symbols matter.

Scholars matter. Of special note, the hood, worn
by holders of doctoral degrees,

signifies the highest level
of academic and professional achievement.

The traditional doctoral
hooding ceremony symbolically marks the
passage of student to scholar.

Congratulations to
the graduates of 2024. We look forward to see
how your scholarship will

move the frontiers
of knowledge and how your passion and your effort
will inspire future generations

and change society
for the better. Thank you. [APPLAUSE]
